solution.p:
We apply the tangent identity to replace \tan \theta by \dfrac{\sin \theta}{\cos \theta} and obtain
            \begin{align*}
                \cos \theta \alert{\tan \theta} + \sin \theta \amp = \cos \theta (\alert{\dfrac{\sin \theta}{\cos \theta}}) + \sin \theta\\
                  \amp = \sin \theta + \sin \theta = 2\sin \theta\\                            
                \end{align*}

We substitute \sin \theta = \dfrac{7}{25} into the Pythagorean identity \cos^2 \theta + \sin^2 \theta = 1 to get
        \begin{align*}
                \cos^2 \theta + (\dfrac{7}{25})^2 \amp = 1 \amp \amp \blert{\text{Isolate } \cos^2 \theta.}\\
                  \cos^2 \theta \amp = 1 - (\dfrac{7}{25})^2 \amp \amp  \textstyle{\blert{1 - (\frac{7}{25})^2 = 1 - \frac{49}{625} = \frac{625-49}{625}}}\\
                  \cos^2 \theta \amp = \dfrac{576}{625} \amp \amp \blert{\text{Take square roots.}}\\
                  \cos \theta \amp = \pm \sqrt{\dfrac{576}{625}} = \pm \dfrac{24}{25}\\                            
                \end{align*}
    Because \theta is between 90\degree and 180\degree, \cos \theta must be negative, so \cos \theta = \dfrac{-24}{25}.  To find \tan \theta, we use the tangent identity.
    \tan \theta = \dfrac{\sin \theta}{\cos \theta} = \dfrac{7/25}{-24/25} = \dfrac{-7}{24}

